Question 1 - Classification vs. Regression¶

Your goal for this project is to identify students who might need early intervention before they fail to graduate. Which type of supervised learning problem is this, classification or regression? Why?

Answer: This is a classification problem because the outcome variable is discrete. The outcome is binary: we either classify a student as in need of early intervention (passed = "yes") or not in need of early intervention (passed = "no").

Preprocess Feature Columns¶

As you can see, there are several non-numeric columns that need to be converted! Many of them are simply yes/no, e.g. internet. These can be reasonably converted into 1/0 (binary) values.

Other columns, like Mjob and Fjob, have more than two values, and are known as categorical variables. The recommended way to handle such a column is to create as many columns as possible values (e.g. Fjob_teacher, Fjob_other, Fjob_services, etc.), and assign a 1 to one of them and 0 to all others.

These generated columns are sometimes called dummy variables, and we will use the pandas.get_dummies() function to perform this transformation. Run the code cell below to perform the preprocessing routine discussed in this section.

In [6]:
def preprocess_features(X):
    ''' Preprocesses the student data and converts non-numeric binary variables into
        binary (0/1) variables. Converts categorical variables into dummy variables. '''
    
    # Initialize new output DataFrame
    output = pd.DataFrame(index = X.index)

    # Investigate each feature column for the data
    for col, col_data in X.iteritems():
        
        # If data type is non-numeric, replace all yes/no values with 1/0
        if col_data.dtype == object:
            col_data = col_data.replace(['yes', 'no'], [1, 0])

        # If data type is categorical, convert to dummy variables
        if col_data.dtype == object:
            # Example: 'school' => 'school_GP' and 'school_MS'
            col_data = pd.get_dummies(col_data, prefix = col)  
        
        # Collect the revised columns
        output = output.join(col_data)
    
    return output

X_all = preprocess_features(X_all)
print "Processed feature columns ({} total features):\n{}".format(len(X_all.columns), list(X_all.columns))

Question 2 - Model Application¶

List three supervised learning models that are appropriate for this problem. What are the general applications of each model? What are their strengths and weaknesses? Given what you know about the data, why did you choose these models to be applied?

Answer:

  1. Decision Trees
    • General Applications: Conceptually, this is a simple model that continues to split the data on various features. The default splitter chooses the feature with the best Gini impurity score. Once the model is trained, it can be represented as a tree and makes for easy interpretation.
    • Strengths: easy to interpret and tune; simple but powerful.
    • Weaknesses: without pruning will be prone to overfitting; there are likely better models.
    • Why This Model?: Decision trees are often considered to be a base model for classification tasks. Under the idea of Occam's Razor, if we can find a decision tree that performs similarly to more complicated models, we would prefer the decision tree. Although the data is somewhat small (only 395 observations with 300 in the training set), there are 48 possible features to split on, which is plenty of features for a variety of splits.

  2. Naive Bayes:
    • General Applications: This model starts with a prior belief about the outcome that gets adjusted based on new information. We saw in the data exploration that 67.09% of students passed their final exam. In this case, the Naive Bayes model would start with a prior of 67.09% and analyze the new information that comes from the features to determine whether a student should be predicted to pass or not.
    • Strengths: training efficiency; useful for a variety of training situations.
    • Weaknesses: assumes features are independent of each other, which may not be valid for all data sets.
    • Why This Model?: We could consider using a k-NN model instead of Naive Bayes here. The main trade-off is that k-NN may fall victim to the curse of dimensionality, whereas Naive Bayes assumes conditional independence of all its features. In the case of this data and k-NN, we only have 395 observations to combat the need for more data as the number of features increases. For Naive Bayes, we might not want to make the assumption of conditional independence of the features. For example, it wouldn't be that surprising if there was a dependence between the extra educational support (schoolsup) feature and the number of prior classes failed (failures) feature. I will use Naive Bayes for this portion of the project, but I will test k-NN in the appendix.

  3. Ensemble (AdaBoost):
    • General Applications: A popular ensemble algorithm that sequentially fits weak learners on subsets of the data. This model is unlikely to overfit on the data even as more weak learners are applied. The default weak learner algorithm is a decision tree, so I would expect the AdaBoost classifier to perform better than the decision tree classifier in (1).
    • Strengths: easy to use; efficient; can improve on other models; usually not prone to overfitting.
    • Weaknesses: performs poorly with uniform noise; may require larger data sets.
    • Why This Model?: I chose this model for all the benefits of decision trees with the additional benefit that it probably performs better than a single decision tree by iterating multiple times.

One more note: It's worth pointing out that all three of these models are "eager" learners. This means they are all going to construct some sort of function from the training data. The benefits are that the models will be able to make fast predictions and require a small amount of storage. The downside is that training the models may take longer than an instance-based model (like k-NN).

Setup¶

Run the code cell below to initialize three helper functions which you can use for training and testing the three supervised learning models you've chosen above. The functions are as follows:

  • train_classifier - takes as input a classifier and training data and fits the classifier to the data.
  • predict_labels - takes as input a fit classifier, features, and a target labeling and makes predictions using the F1 score.
  • train_predict - takes as input a classifier, and the training and testing data, and performs train_clasifier and predict_labels.
    • This function will report the F1 score for both the training and testing data separately.
In [8]:
def train_classifier(clf, X_train, y_train):
    ''' Fits a classifier to the training data. '''
    
    # Start the clock, train the classifier, then stop the clock
    start = time()
    clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    end = time()
    
    # Print the results
    print "Trained model in {:.4f} seconds".format(end - start)

    
def predict_labels(clf, features, target):
    ''' Makes predictions using a fit classifier based on F1 score. '''
    
    # Start the clock, make predictions, then stop the clock
    start = time()
    y_pred = clf.predict(features)
    end = time()
    
    # Print and return results
    print "Made predictions in {:.4f} seconds.".format(end - start)
    return f1_score(target.values, y_pred, pos_label='yes')


def train_predict(clf, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test):
    ''' Train and predict using a classifer based on F1 score. '''
    
    # Indicate the classifier and the training set size
    print "Training a {} using a training set size of {}. . .".format(clf.__class__.__name__, len(X_train))
    
    # Train the classifier
    train_classifier(clf, X_train, y_train)
    
    # Print the results of prediction for both training and testing
    print "F1 score for training set: {:.4f}.".format(predict_labels(clf, X_train, y_train))
    print "F1 score for test set: {:.4f}.".format(predict_labels(clf, X_test, y_test))

Question 3 - Chosing the Best Model¶

Based on the experiments you performed earlier, in one to two paragraphs, explain to the board of supervisors what single model you chose as the best model. Which model is generally the most appropriate based on the available data, limited resources, cost, and performance?

Answer: According to the model scores, the best model is the ensemble AdaBoost Classifier. When trained on the full training set, it has the highest F1 Score of any of the 3 models on the testing set.

With that said, there are some other factors the board of supervisors should take into consideration. All the models were able to train in less than one-tenth of a second, but AdaBoost clearly took the longest. The short training time is likely due to the fact that the data is currently very small at only 300 records in the training data. If the program is only going to be local, it is probably fine to stick with the AdaBoost model. If there are plans to expand state-wide or nationally, we may want to consider tuning a decision tree model for training time purposes.

We would also like to know which features are most important in the model so we can develop programs to target changes to these features. For example, if having internet access at home is very important, we could consider programs to give families subsidized internet.

Question 4 - Model in Layman's Terms¶

In one to two paragraphs, explain to the board of directors in layman's terms how the final model chosen is supposed to work. For example if you've chosen to use a decision tree or a support vector machine, how does the model go about making a prediction?

Answer: The final model is a boosted Decision Tree. The process has two parts: the Decision Tree algorithm and the boosting.

1. Decision Tree Model The decision tree model takes the labeled training data and uses an algorithm to create successive nodes that split the data. As a hypothetical, imagine that 40 of the 300 students have internet at home and all 40 pass their exams. The model could create its first split on the internet variable. It would classify the 40 students who have internet as passed = "yes". We call this a terminal node, which simply means that for these 40 students the decision tree stops here. Of the remaining 260 students, the algorithm now looks for another feature which does a good job at splitting the data. The model continues to classify the data in this manner until it terminates.

2. Boosting Boosting is a more technical method of improving model fit. Essentially it successively repeats the Decision Tree Model from step 1 on subsets of the data, checks which specific data point it got wrong, and then gives the incorrect data points greater importance in successive repetitions of the process. It allows us to create better models, frequently without the risk of overfitting.

Implementation: Model Tuning¶

Fine tune the chosen model. Use grid search (GridSearchCV) with at least one important parameter tuned with at least 3 different values. You will need to use the entire training set for this. In the code cell below, you will need to implement the following:

  • Import sklearn.grid_search.gridSearchCV and sklearn.metrics.make_scorer.
  • Create a dictionary of parameters you wish to tune for the chosen model.
    • Example: parameters = {'parameter' : [list of values]}.
  • Initialize the classifier you've chosen and store it in clf.
  • Create the F1 scoring function using make_scorer and store it in f1_scorer.
    • Set the pos_label parameter to the correct value!
  • Perform grid search on the classifier clf using f1_scorer as the scoring method, and store it in grid_obj.
  • Fit the grid search object to the training data (X_train, y_train), and store it in grid_obj.
In [10]:
# TODO: Import 'GridSearchCV' and 'make_scorer'
from sklearn.grid_search import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.metrics import make_scorer

# TODO: Create the parameters list you wish to tune
parameters = {'n_estimators':[1,5,25,50,75,100]}

# TODO: Initialize the classifier
clf = AdaBoostClassifier()

# TODO: Make an f1 scoring function using 'make_scorer' 
f1_scorer = make_scorer(f1_score, pos_label='yes')

# TODO: Perform grid search on the classifier using the f1_scorer as the scoring method
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(estimator=clf, param_grid=parameters, scoring=f1_scorer)

# TODO: Fit the grid search object to the training data and find the optimal parameters
grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Get the estimator
clf = grid_obj.best_estimator_

# Report the final F1 score for training and testing after parameter tuning
print "Tuned model has a training F1 score of {:.4f}.".format(predict_labels(clf, X_train, y_train))
print "Tuned model has a testing F1 score of {:.4f}.".format(predict_labels(clf, X_test, y_test))

That's a big tree! We are probably overfitting the data. If we zoom in, the first split is on the failures feature, which is the number of prior classes a student has failed. It's not surprising that this would be a good indicator of graduation.

Pruning¶

Let's create a new classifier that prunes our tree.

In [25]:
clf_DT = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=3, min_samples_split = 10, random_state=123)

train_predict(clf_DT, X_train_300, y_train_300, X_test, y_test)

dot_data = StringIO()
tree.export_graphviz(clf_DT, out_file=dot_data, feature_names = list(X_all.columns), class_names=['no','yes'], 
                     filled=True, rounded=True, special_characters=True)
graph = pydotplus.graph_from_dot_data(dot_data.getvalue())
Image(graph.create_png())

Training a DecisionTreeClassifier using a training set size of 300. . .
Trained model in 0.0010 seconds
Made predictions in 0.0000 seconds.
F1 score for training set: 0.8315.
Made predictions in 0.0000 seconds.
F1 score for test set: 0.8514.
Out[25]:

By pruning the decision tree, we move from an F1 score on the test set of 0.7612 to 0.8514. We also get a clearer picture of how our decision tree works. Take the far left path:

  1. Student has failed 0 classes.
  2. Students has fewer than 18 absences.
  3. Students is male.
  4. Classify student as passed = 'yes'.

One interesting part is that the split on gender doesn't make a difference at this node. The 98 female students also get classified as passed = 'yes'.
